{{Infobox civilian attack | title = Missionaries of Charity attack in Aden | partof = [[Yemeni Civil War (2015–present)|Yemen Civil War]] and [[Aden unrest (2015–present)|Aden unrest]] | image = {{Location map|Yemen |alt = Aden. |lat_deg = 12.881921 |lon_deg = 45.031703 }} | image_size = | alt = Missionaries of Charity attack in Aden | caption = | map = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | location = [[Aden]], [[Yemen]] | target = [[Christians]] | date = {{start date|2016|03|04|df=yes}} | fatalities = 16 | perps = [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]<ref name="hindustantimes1">{{cite web|url=http://m.hindustantimes.com/world-news/indian-priest-kidnapped-by-is-makes-emotional-plea-for-help/story-PGVv09WsYDRc2DOkcPrLII.html|title=I’m not of value because I’m Indian: Priest abducted by Islamic State seeks help|website=M.hindustantimes.com|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref>(alleged, denied) | weapons = Firearms | numparts = 4 }}
{{Campaignbox Yemeni Crisis}}
'''The Missionaries of Charity attack in Aden''' was a [[mass murder]] crime committed by unknown gunmen inside a home for older people in [[Aden]], [[Yemen]] on 4 March 2016.<ref name="nytimes.com">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/05/world/middleeast/gunmen-kill-14-at-nursing-home-in-yemen-started-by-mother-teresa.html|title=Gunmen Kill 16 at Nursing Home in Yemen Started by Mother Teresa|date=5 March 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
16 people were killed including four [[Catholicism|Catholic]] nuns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/here-are-the-faces-of-the-nuns-who-were-martyred-in-yemen-84893|title=Here are the faces of the nuns who were martyred in Yemen|work=Catholic News Agency|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> An Indian priest, Tom Ozhonaniel, was kidnapped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/yemen-gunmen-kidnap-indian-priest-care-home-where-16-including-4-nuns-were-slaughtered-1547876|title=Yemen: Gunmen kidnap Indian priest from care home where 16 including 4 nuns were slaughtered|author=William Watkinson|work=International Business Times UK|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
The identities of the attackers are unknown. Media outlets published a statement attributed to [[Ansar al-Sharia]], one of the active [[jihadist]] organizations in the country, denies any relation to the incident.<ref name="qaeda">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/03/06/middleeast/yemen-attack-qaeda-denies-link|title=Al Qaeda denies link to attack that killed nuns in Yemen|author=Faith Karimi, CNN|date=6 March 2016|work=CNN|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world/missing-indian-priest-in-yemen-abducted-by-terrorists-sushma-swaraj/story-hYxUiPYtLFdlfswm7qvdZM.html|title=Missing Indian priest in Yemen abducted by 'terrorists': Sushma Swaraj|work=Hindustantimes|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
''[[The Times of India]]'' posited the attackers belonged to the Yemen-based affiliate of the Islamic State (ISIS) group.<ref name="hindustantimes1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/middle-east-news/Senior-Indian-nun-of-Yemen-aid-home-to-be-evacuated/articleshow/51297336.cms|title=Senior Indian nun of Yemen aid home to be evacuated|date=7 March 2016|work=The Times of India|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="nytimes.com"/>
==Background== {{See also|Christianity in Yemen}} Christian presence in [[Yemen]] goes back to the fourth century AD to hold a number of [[Himyarite Kingdom|Himyarites]] believers due to the efforts of [[Theophilos the Indian]]. Currently, there are no official statistics on their numbers, but estimated at between 3,000 and 25,000 people,<ref name="us">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2008/108496.htm|title=Yemen|work=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> and most of them are refugees or temporary residents.
[[Freedom of worship]], conversion from Islam and establishing facilities dedicated for worship are not recognized in the Constitution or as laws or legal rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/193127.pdf|format=PDF|title=Yemen : Executive summary|website=State.gov|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> At the same time, [[Wahhabism|Wahabbi]] activities linked to [[Al-Islah (Yemen)|Al-Islah]] were being facilitated, financed and encouraged from multiple fronts including the Ministry of Endowments and Guidance,<ref>{{cite book|author=Shelagh Weir|title=A Tribal Order: Politics and Law in the Mountains of Yemen|date=2009|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=9780292773974|quote=''These activities were encouraged and financed, as elsewhere in Yemen, by the then Wahhabi-controlled Ministry of Religious Guidance (irsha ̄d), by Saudi and Yemeni business figures and by the Yemeni Reform Grouping islah''|page=296}}</ref> which says that its tasks "to contribute to the development of Islamic awareness and circulation of the publication Education and Islamic morals and consolidation in the life of public and private citizens."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yemen-nic.info/ministations/section.php?SECTION_ID=452|title=وزارة الأوقاف والإرشاد|publisher=|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
The Missionaries of Charity, founded by [[Mother Teresa]], have worked in Aden since 1992, and the order has three other centers in [[Sana'a]], [[Taiz]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Hodeidah]]. Three Catholic nuns were killed in Hodeidah in 1998, two from India and the third from the Philippines, at the hands of a member of Al-Islah Abdullah al-Nashiri, arguing that they were calling for conversion to [[Christianity]]. In 2002, three Americans were killed in Baptists Hospital at the hands of another Al-Islah member named Abed Abdul Razak Kamel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/205561/too-deep-evan-kohlmann|title=National Review Online|author=Evan Kohlmann|date=17 January 2003|work=National Review Online|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> Survivors say that the hospital was "a political football" often raised by Islamists (Al-Islah), who talked about it in mosques and hospital workers describing Hospital workers as "spies". But they emphasized that these opinions are a minority among Yemenis.<ref name="nytimes.com1">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/16/world/threats-and-responses-victims-nine-bullets-that-ended-baptists-work-in-yemen.html|title=Nine Bullets That Ended Baptists' Work in Yemen|date=16 January 2003|work=The New York Times|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
In December 2015, a Catholic church in Aden was destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/gunmen-kill-16-at-retirement-home-in-aden-1457094756|title=Gunmen Kill 16 at Yemeni Home for the Elderly|author=Saleh al-Batati in Yemen and Asa Fitch in Dubai|date=6 March 2016|work=WSJ|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> Since the escalation of the Yemeni crisis in March 2015, six priests from [[John Bosco]] remained, and twenty workers of charitable missions in the country, described by [[Pope Francis]] by the courage to fortitude amid war and conflict. He called the [[Apostolic Vicar]] of Southern Arabia to pray for all the oppressed and tortured, expelled from their homes, and killed unjustly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americamagazine.org/issue/catholics-yemen|title=Catholics in Yemen|work=America Magazine|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> The Missionaries of Charity were not actively engaged in [[Evangelism|evangelization]] according to the testimonies of beneficiaries of its services.<ref name="nytimes.com1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2002/12/30/three-american-missionaries-killed-in-yemen-hospital.html|title=Three American Missionaries Killed in Yemen Hospital|work=Fox News|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
==Attack== The attack on the house took place at 12:00pm local time, when two armed men had persuaded the guards to let them through the main gate having claimed they were going to visit their elderly mother. Once they entered, they began to shoot randomly, according to Indian officials at the Foreign Ministry.<ref name="indianexpress.com">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/4-indian-nurses-among-16-dead-in-yemen-gun-attack-govt-verifying-reports|title=Indian nun among 16 killed by gunmen in Yemen; victims handcuffed, shot in the head|date=5 March 2016|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
Inside the building, nuns were preparing breakfast. Four of the five nuns sensed danger and tried to hide in a convent, where they were shot dead in an open area. All the rooms were stormed and the meeting tent was destroyed, as were statues and crucifixes in the small church. In one picture, two nuns are shown lying on the ground in a dirt yard, after having been shot [[Capital punishment|execution-style]]. The attackers were dressed in a "semi-blue" uniform.<ref name="indianexpress.com"/> According to the [[Catholic News Agency]], the last prayer said by the nuns before they were killed says:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/theres-no-question-the-missionaries-of-charity-died-as-martyrs-52544/|title=There's no question – the Missionaries of Charity in Yemen 'died as martyrs'|work=Catholic News Agency|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> {{Quote|Lord, teach me to be [[Generosity|generous]]. Teach me to serve you as you deserve; to give and not to count the cost, to fight and not to heed the wounds, to toil and not to seek for rest, to labor and not to ask for reward.}}
Sunita Kumar, a spokesman for the charity's mission, described the killers as "demented", adding "there is no other explanation as to why armed people would enter the premises of the home and shoot down innocent, harmless nurses who had dedicated their lives to serving others."<ref name="indianexpress.com"/> Bishop Michael Lewis of the Anglican Church said the compound contained seventy or eighty elderly people, many destitute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anglicannews.org/news/2016/03/prayers-offered-after-killing-of-nuns-in-yemen.aspx|title=Prayers offered after killing of nuns in Yemen|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> The [[Cardinal Secretary of State]] [[Pietro Parolin]] commented that [[Pope Francis]] prayed that this pointless slaughter will awaken consciences, lead to a change of heart and inspire all parties to lay down their arms and take up the path of dialogue.<ref name="qaeda"/>
Pope Francis described the crime as "satanic", stating that the nuns were "martyrs of today", adding that they were killed by both the attackers, and a "globalization of indifference.". His statement was published, including the following quote:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americamagazine.org/content/dispatches/pope-says-four-nuns-were-killed-yemen-their-attackers-and-globalization|title=Pope Francis says nuns killed in Yemen attack are victims of ‘the globalization of indifference’|work=America Magazine|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> {{Quote|In the name of God, he calls upon all parties in the present conflict to renounce violence, and to renew their commitment to the people of Yemen, particularly those most in need, whom the Sisters and their helpers sought to serve.}}
The Missionaries of Charity announced it would continue its work in Yemen despite the violence and danger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/news/headlines/index.cfm?storyid=27700|title=Missionaries of Charity pledge to continue work in Yemen|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>
==Victims== {| class="wikitable centre sortable" |+ Deaths by nationality !Country !Number !Ref. |- | {{flagu|Yemen}} ! 7 !<ref name="google1">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.it/amp/www.catholicnewsagency.com/amp/news/four-sisters-dead-in-attack-on-missionaries-of-charity-home-in-yemen-99801/?client=ms-android-h3g-it|title=UPDATED: Four sisters dead in attack on Missionaries of Charity home in Yemen: Catholic News Agency (CNA)|website=Google.it|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> |- | {{flagu|Ethiopia}} ! 5 !<ref name="google1"/> |- | {{flagu|Rwanda}} ! 2 !<ref name="google1"/> |- | {{flagu|India}} ! 1 !<ref name="google1"/> |- | {{flagu|Kenya}} ! 1 !<ref name="google1"/> |- class="sortbottom" |'''Total''' ! 16 !<ref name="google1"/> |} An Indian priest, Tom Ozhonaniel, was also kidnapped. Since, he has appeared in several videos chastising the lack of effort to release him and pleading for his life.<ref name="hindustantimes1"/><ref name="The Times of India 2016">{{cite web | title=Abducted Indian priest to pope: Being ignored as I am not European | website=The Times of India | date=2016-12-26 | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/abducted-malayali-priest-begs-for-life-in-video/articleshow/56187113.cms | access-date=2018-02-06}}</ref><ref name="Vatican Radio 2017">{{cite web | title=Fr. Tom kidnapped Indian priest in Yemen pleads for help in video | website=Vatican Radio | date=2017-05-10 | url=http://en.radiovaticana.va/news/2017/05/10/fr_tom_kidnapped_indian_priest_in_pleads_for_help_in_video/1311222 | language=la | access-date=2018-02-06}}</ref>
